\description{
Computes rolling-window spectral metrics for a univariate time series,
estimating the spectral exponent (beta) and spectral ratio to detect
shifts in noise colour that precede critical transitions. Reddening of
the power spectrum (increasing beta) is a hallmark of critical slowing
down.
}
\details{
The analysis proceeds in four stages:

\strong{1. Window extraction.} A rolling window of size \code{window} slides
across the series with the specified \code{align}ment. Each window
position produces one set of spectral metrics.

\strong{2. Detrending.} Before computing the spectrum, each window segment
is detrended according to \code{detrend}:
\itemize{
\item \code{"none"}: No detrending. Suitable when the data are already
stationary within each window.
\item \code{"linear"} (default): Removes a least-squares linear trend
from each window. Appropriate for slowly drifting series.
\item \code{"diff"}: First-differences the window segment. Effective
for integrated (unit-root) processes but reduces the segment
length by one observation.
}

\strong{3. Spectral estimation.} The power spectral density is estimated
by one of two methods:
\itemize{
\item \code{"periodogram"} (default): Computes the raw periodogram via
\code{\link[stats:spectrum]{stats::spectrum()}} with \code{method = "pgram"}. Fast and
nonparametric. A 10 percent cosine taper is applied by default.
\item \code{"ar"}: Fits an autoregressive model and derives the spectrum
via \code{\link[stats:spectrum]{stats::spectrum()}} with \code{method = "ar"}. Smoother estimates,
but assumes the AR model is appropriate.
}

\strong{4. Metrics and classification.} For each window:
\itemize{
\item The \strong{spectral exponent} (beta) is the negative slope of the
log(power) vs. log(frequency) regression. Positive beta indicates
reddened spectra (more low-frequency power). Rising beta over time
signals critical slowing down.
\item The \strong{spectral ratio} is the ratio of total power at
frequencies below the median to total power above the median.
Values > 1 indicate a red-shifted spectrum.
\item The \strong{R-squared} of the log-log regression quantifies how
well the power-law model fits the spectrum.
}

\strong{State classification} based on the spectral exponent:
\itemize{
\item beta < 0.5: \code{white_noise} -- uncorrelated fluctuations
with flat spectrum.
\item 0.5 <= beta < 1.5: \code{pink_noise} -- 1/f-like
dynamics, moderate long-range correlations.
\item 1.5 <= beta < 2.5: \code{red_noise} -- strong low-frequency
dominance, consistent with critical slowing down.
\item beta >= 2.5: \code{brownian} -- Brownian-motion-like
dynamics with very strong low-frequency power.
}

\strong{Edge padding.} Window positions at the series boundaries that lack
sufficient data are filled by a three-step strategy: (1) forward-fill
from the first valid estimate to the series start, (2) backward-fill
from the last valid estimate to the series end, and (3) linear
interpolation for any internal gaps.
}
